    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-09-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="529" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Pike</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Seward</persName>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 175.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United States Legation,</hi>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Hague,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-09-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">September</hi> 13, 1865.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I am without any of your favors since my
                            last, excepting your No. 248. The annual ceremony of opening the
                            legislative chambers takes place the 18th instant, for which the King
                            and his ministers have already returned to town. The two bodies contrive
                            to have about a dozen sessions a year between them. They practice a very
                            old-fashioned and cumbrous form of legislation, as you may suppose, or
                            they would have no need of such frequent sittings.</p>
                <p>The cattle plague has at length reached Holland, and spread in the
                            interior. It is naturally regarded with alarm in a country so full of
                            domestic animals as this, especially of the bovine race.</p>
                <p>The apprehended visitation of the cholera is now but little feared, as
                            the cool weather already approaches.</p>
                <p>The crops in this part of Europe are generally good, in this country
                            especially so.</p>
                <p>In England there has been much complaint, but the apprehensions of a bad
                            harvest are less now than they were a fortnight ago, the weather since
                            then having been remarkably fine.</p>
                <p>Still, prices have risen, and paying rates for our breadstuffs and
                            provisions seem likely to prevail, a circumstance favorable to our
                            finances.</p>
                <p>I have the honor to be, with great respect, your most obedient
                            servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES S. PIKE.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State.</hi>
                    </p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
